# .gitignore

# This file is ignored by Git, so it will not be tracked or committed to the repository.
#
# It's used for keeping track of files that are specific to your project and should not be included in version control.

# Example:
# /path/to/project/src/components/MyComponent.js

This .gitignore file contains a list of paths that Git should ignore when tracking changes. This is useful if you have sensitive or personal information stored on the local machine, as it will prevent those files from being committed to your version control repository.

Note: The example provided here is just for demonstration purposes and does not contain any actual content relevant to the project mentioned in the question.